            <fr:title text="Fibre products of schemes are topological">Fibre products of schemes are topological</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X,Y,S]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link href="/schm-86OJ/" title="Scheme" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-86OJ/" display-uri="schm-86OJ" type="local">schemes</fr:link> with morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : X \to  S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g : Y \to  S]]></fr:tex>. Then the pullback <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \times _S Y]]></fr:tex> exists in the category of schemes, and its underlying topological space is the pullback in the category of topological spaces.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>11</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    The existence of the fibre products follows from the usual gluing argument for schemes, and reduces to the fibre products of affine schemes. For affine schemes, the fibre products are computed by the spectrum of <fr:link href="/idem-comm-A6ON/" title="Pushouts of algebras are tensor products" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-A6ON/" display-uri="idem-comm-A6ON" type="local">pushouts</fr:link>, because we have seen from <fr:link href="/schm-X3M9/" title="Universal property of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-X3M9/" display-uri="schm-X3M9" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-X3M9/" display-uri="schm-X3M9" /></fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}]]></fr:tex> is a right adjoint.
  </html:p>
  <html:p />
